# 4. Core Components

Atlas is composed of independent modules.

Each module has a single responsibility.

### Authentication

Responsible for:

- user registration
- login
- session management
- permissions

---

### Profile Service

Stores permanent user information.

Examples:

- nationality
- destination country
- profession
- languages
- immigration goals

---

### Case Management

Represents one real-world process.

Examples:

- Move to Spain
- Residence Renewal
- Family Reunification
- Citizenship Application

A single user may own multiple Cases.

---

### Journey Engine

Tracks the progress of each Case.

Responsibilities:

- progress calculation
- current stage
- completed missions
- timeline

---

### Mission Engine

Transforms complex bureaucracy into structured objectives.

Mission

↓

Tasks

↓

Completion

---

### Document Service

Responsible for:

- secure upload
- OCR
- validation
- categorization
- expiration tracking

---

### Notification Engine

Atlas does not send engagement notifications.

Notifications are generated only when they create value.

Examples:

- upcoming deadline
- missing document
- legal update affecting the user's Case
- appointment reminder

---

### Conversation Engine

The chatbot is not the product.

The chatbot is an interface to the Atlas Intelligence Engine.

Every conversation must consider:

- user profile
- active Case
- journey stage
- uploaded documents
- previous conversations

---

# 5. Atlas Intelligence Engine (AIE)

The AIE is the central component of the platform.

It coordinates all intelligent behavior.

Submodules include:

- Diagnostic Engine
- Planning Engine
- Journey Engine
- Conversation Engine
- Notification Engine

Every future Atlas product will reuse this engine.

---

# 6. Diagnostic First

No AI conversation should occur before an initial diagnosis.

Users first complete an adaptive assessment.

Only after sufficient context has been collected may conversational assistance begin.

This principle is mandatory across all Atlas products.

---

# 7. Adaptive Diagnostic

The diagnostic process is dynamic.

Each answer determines the next question.

This prevents unnecessary questions while increasing personalization.

The diagnostic ends only when Atlas has enough information to generate a reliable action plan.

---

# 8. AI Workflow

Every AI response follows the same pipeline.

User Request

↓

Load Profile

↓

Load Active Case

↓

Load Journey

↓

Retrieve Relevant Documents

↓

Search Official Knowledge Base

↓

Generate Context

↓

Produce Response

↓

Persist Relevant Memory

The AI never answers without context.

---

# 9. Knowledge Architecture

Atlas relies on Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG).

Only trusted information should be retrieved.

Sources include:

- government websites
- immigration agencies
- official legislation
- consulates
- ministries

Every retrieved document must include:

- source
- publication date
- country
- language
- version

---

# 10. Data Storage

The platform separates information into different storage systems.

### PostgreSQL

Structured business data.

### Object Storage

Uploaded files.

### Vector Database

Semantic search.

### Redis

Caching.

---

# 11. Scalability

Every service must be replaceable.

Examples:

- AI provider
- storage provider
- vector database
- authentication service

Business logic must remain independent from infrastructure.

---

# 12. Security

Atlas adopts privacy by design.

Requirements:

- encrypted communication
- encrypted storage for sensitive data
- authentication required for all private resources
- audit logs
- secure backups
- least privilege access

---

# 13. Engineering Principles

Every module should satisfy:

- single responsibility
- loose coupling
- high cohesion
- clear interfaces
- testability
- documentation

---

# 14. Future Products

The architecture must support:

- Atlas Immigration
- Atlas Legal
- Atlas Finance
- Atlas Health
- Atlas Education

without redesigning the core infrastructure.

---

# 15. Architecture Principles

The following principles are mandatory.

1. Diagnose before advising.

2. Context before conversation.

3. Trust before automation.

4. Simplicity before complexity.

5. Platform before product.

---

16. Build for Evolution
Every major architectural decision must make future evolution easier, not harder.

# Decision Summary

Atlas is built as an AI platform centered around the Atlas Intelligence Engine.

Every product shares the same architectural principles while implementing domain-specific business logic.

The architecture prioritizes modularity, scalability, transparency, and long-term maintainability.

